               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1207" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1207" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1207" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1207" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN ALLEN.</persName>
                  </hi> I am the wife of George Allen, of Suffolk-street, Southwark—the prisoner is my son—this shawl, frock, and two aprons, are mine (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>)—my boy was charged with stealing them—he said he had taken them.—(<hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">objected to any confession of Allen's, implica<lb></lb>ting Challander, being given; Allen not being on his trial [see Rex v. Turner</hi>, 1<hi rend="italic">st Moody's Crown Cases, page</hi> 347.]—<hi rend="italic">Allen's confession was not received.</hi>)—in consequence of what he said to me, I went with Wise to Chal<lb></lb>lander's house—he asked her if she had bought a shawl—she denied it—she had the apron on—Wise searched, and found some pawnbroker's tickets—he said, "Here is a ticket for a shawl"—she said that was not the shawl; that was her own—we went to the pawnbroker's, and found my shawl.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184802280177"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did not she say the ticket was for her daughter's shawl? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> She may; I did not hear what she said to the policeman—It is not a large room—I was on the other side to the policeman—I said, "That is my apron"—she said, "If it is yours take it."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1208" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1208" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1208" type="surname" value="WISE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1208" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN WISE</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman, M</hi> 84.) I took Allen, and then went with his father and mother to Challander's—I asked if she recollected buying some shawls, a child's frock, and some apron of a boy—she said she brought a frock of a boy for 4<hi rend="italic">d</hi>.—I asked of she had brought any shawls—she said, "No"—I asked if she would allow me to search—she said, "Yes"—I searched, and in a drawer under the bedstead I found a child's frock—I asked where the apron were—she handed over one, which Mrs. Allen did not identify; but she did the one she wore—I saw Wild find a ticket for the shawl; it was shown to the prisoner—she said it was her daughter's shawl.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1209" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1209" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1209" type="surname" value="WILD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1209" type="given" value="GEORGE"></interp>GEORGE WILD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman.</hi>) I am at the house, and after the prisoner had said that was all the. duplicates she had, I found three in an image on the shelf—I said, "Here is something relating to a shawl"—she said, "That is my daughter's—I went with Mr. and Mrs. Allen to Mr. Bennett, a pawn<lb></lb>broker's, in St. George's-circus, produced the ticket, and this shawl was pro<lb></lb>duced—as I was going out at the door, I said, "I shall go and see your daughter"—the prisoner said, "Don't trouble yourself, for that is the shawl I brought of the boy Allen; I gave him 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. for it."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Have you said that before? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I do not know that I have—the other witness were outside the door then—she went before the Magistrate to indentify the boy, and then said the gave 15<hi rend="italic">d</hi>. for it—she was then taken in charge—I did not take ker at the time, as I had a sum<lb></lb>mons for her as a witness—Mr. Cottingham did not reprimand me—the clerk said I ought to have taken her into custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18480228-name-1210" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1210" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1210" type="surname" value="BARNETT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18480228-name-1210" type="given" value="CATHERINE"></interp>CATHERINE BARNETT.</persName>
                  </hi> I live at 21, Fleet-street. On Saturday morning, two days before this charge, Allen came and offered me this shawl for 18<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and said his mother wanted to sell it—I said, "I can only give him 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>."—he said, "My mother will not take less than 18<hi rend="italic">d</hi>."—he took it to another house in the street—he said his mother was in great distress.</p>
               <p>(Challander received a good character)</p>
